                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d672">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00112 European War 1939/7621: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Sweden</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stockholm</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-01-13T15:00:00+01:00"
                            >January 13, 1943—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 13—1:28 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>132. Boheman has just called to say that Government has taken the formal decision
                    with approval of Foreign Affairs Committee of Riksdag which was communicated
                    informally to Mallet and Greene on January 11 (see Legation’s 109, January 11, 6
                    p.m.). Everything is accordingly all clear as soon as British and American
                    Governments have accepted four conditions mentioned in that telegram (see also
                    Legation’s 129, January 13, noon<note n="15" xml:id="d672fn15">Not
                        printed.</note>).</p>
                <p>Repeated to London.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
